>Opening my eyes proved easy enough, though I did so slowly at first. Keeping out the bright overhead lights was more important than finally figuring out where I was. A singular bright white blob shrunk into several smaller spots, until those too receded from my vision and my eyesight was mostly clear, if a little blurry. What I had thought were stars dotting the sky turned into fluorescent lights on a starkly white ceiling devoid of any other features. Even attempting to turn my head brought with it a painful ache, so I looked around as best I could with just my eyes. The walls were as empty as the ceiling, save for a lone black stripe that ran around the perimeter halfway up. A beeping machine drew my attention to a host of other electronics by my bedside, and I noticed then where I lay was a bed; more like a hollowed-out tube, much like what I had seen in Freddie's infirmary.
